Note:
BOUNDING_BOX - Axis-aligned geographic bounding box (BBox)

A BoundingBox is an axis-aligned rectangle in latitude/longitude space.
It is the standard primitive for spatial indexing, tile selection,
viewport queries, and pre-filtering points before a heavier geodesic
calculation.

REPRESENTATION

  min_lat_deg, max_lat_deg  - latitude span (degrees), [-90, +90]
  min_lon_deg, max_lon_deg  - longitude span (degrees), [-180, +180]

ANTIMERIDIAN HANDLING

  A bbox where min_lon > max_lon is INTERPRETED as crossing the
  antimeridian (the +/-180 deg meridian): the included longitudes are
  [min_lon, +180] union [-180, max_lon]. This convention follows
  GeoJSON RFC 7946 section 5.2 and is the right behaviour for boxes
  that wrap around the Pacific.

OPERATIONS

  bbox_create                     - explicit constructor
  bbox_from_points                - smallest bbox containing both points
  bbox_expand_to_include          - return bbox enlarged to include point
  bbox_union                      - smallest bbox containing two bboxes
  bbox_intersection               - bbox-bbox intersection (possibly empty)
  bbox_contains_point             - point-in-bbox test
  bbox_contains_bbox              - whole-containment test
  bbox_intersects                 - bbox-bbox overlap test
  bbox_center                     - center point (lat, lon)
  bbox_area_approx_km2            - rough surface area (degrees-squared
                                    interpretation, no projection)
  bbox_split_at_antimeridian      - returns 1 or 2 sub-bboxes
                                    (caller pre-allocates a buffer)
  bbox_crosses_antimeridian       - boolean predicate

CITATIONS

  - RFC 7946 (2016): "The GeoJSON Format", IETF. Section 5.2 specifies
    the antimeridian-crossing bbox convention.
  - Open Geospatial Consortium (OGC) standards (WFS, WMS) describe the
    same wrapping convention with the same min_lon > max_lon semantics.
  - PostGIS ST_Envelope and Google S2 ShapeIndex use compatible models.
:End Note

Import "compiler/frontend/primitives/core/arithmetic_core.runa" as Arith

Note: ============================================================================
Note: SECTION 1 - BoundingBox struct
Note: ============================================================================

Type called "BoundingBox":
    min_lat_deg as Float
    max_lat_deg as Float
    min_lon_deg as Float
    max_lon_deg as Float
End Type

Note: ============================================================================
Note: SECTION 2 - Constructors
Note: ============================================================================

Process called "bbox_create" takes min_lat as Float, max_lat as Float, min_lon as Float, max_lon as Float returns BoundingBox:
    @Reasoning:
        Direct constructor. The caller is responsible for the
        antimeridian-crossing convention (min_lon may legally exceed
        max_lon when the bbox wraps).
    @End Reasoning
    @Implementation:
        Stores four fields. No normalisation - the convention is to
        preserve min_lon > max_lon for wrapping bboxes.
    @End Implementation
    @Performance_Hints:
        Four stores.
    @End Performance_Hints
    @Security_Scope:
        Pure.
    @End Security_Scope
    Let bb be a value of type BoundingBox
    Set bb.min_lat_deg to min_lat
    Set bb.max_lat_deg to max_lat
    Set bb.min_lon_deg to min_lon
    Set bb.max_lon_deg to max_lon
    Return bb
End Process

Process called "bbox_from_point" takes lat_deg as Float, lon_deg as Float returns BoundingBox:
    Note: Degenerate bbox containing only a single point.
    Return proc bbox_create with lat_deg, lat_deg, lon_deg, lon_deg
End Process

Process called "bbox_from_points" takes lat_a as Float, lon_a as Float, lat_b as Float, lon_b as Float returns BoundingBox:
    @Reasoning:
        Build the smallest axis-aligned bbox in lat/lon space
        containing two given points. Does NOT handle antimeridian
        wrapping: if the two points are on opposite sides of the
        antimeridian the user-supplied "smallest" bbox is ambiguous,
        and we return the bbox that does NOT cross the antimeridian.
        Callers needing the wrapping variant should construct it via
        bbox_create with explicit min_lon > max_lon.
    @End Reasoning
    @Implementation:
        Min and max of each coordinate independently.
    @End Implementation
    @Performance_Hints:
        Four compares.
    @End Performance_Hints
    @Security_Scope:
        Pure.
    @End Security_Scope
    Let min_lat be lat_a
    Let max_lat be lat_b
    If lat_a is greater than lat_b:
        Set min_lat to lat_b
        Set max_lat to lat_a
    End If
    Let min_lon be lon_a
    Let max_lon be lon_b
    If lon_a is greater than lon_b:
        Set min_lon to lon_b
        Set max_lon to lon_a
    End If
    Return proc bbox_create with min_lat, max_lat, min_lon, max_lon
End Process

Process called "bbox_expand_to_include" takes bb as BoundingBox, lat_deg as Float, lon_deg as Float returns BoundingBox:
    @Reasoning:
        Return a new bbox that extends bb to include the supplied point.
        If the bbox crosses the antimeridian we choose to extend the
        non-wrapping side that requires less expansion.
    @End Reasoning
    @Implementation:
        For latitude: clamp into [min_lat..max_lat]. For longitude when
        the bbox does NOT cross the antimeridian: clamp into
        [min_lon..max_lon]. For longitude when the bbox DOES cross,
        the convention min_lon > max_lon means the included region is
        [min_lon, +180] U [-180, max_lon]; if the point lies in that
        region we return bb unchanged; otherwise we extend on the side
        requiring the smaller absolute expansion.
    @End Implementation
    @Performance_Hints:
        Four compares + possibly four stores.
    @End Performance_Hints
    @Security_Scope:
        Pure.
    @End Security_Scope
    Let new_min_lat be bb.min_lat_deg
    Let new_max_lat be bb.max_lat_deg
    If lat_deg is less than new_min_lat:
        Set new_min_lat to lat_deg
    End If
    If lat_deg is greater than new_max_lat:
        Set new_max_lat to lat_deg
    End If
    Let new_min_lon be bb.min_lon_deg
    Let new_max_lon be bb.max_lon_deg
    Let crosses be 0
    If bb.min_lon_deg is greater than bb.max_lon_deg:
        Set crosses to 1
    End If
    If crosses is equal to 0:
        Note: standard bbox - either extend min or max
        If lon_deg is less than new_min_lon:
            Set new_min_lon to lon_deg
        End If
        If lon_deg is greater than new_max_lon:
            Set new_max_lon to lon_deg
        End If
    Otherwise:
        Note: wrapping bbox - already includes [min, +180] U [-180, max]
        Let in_region be 0
        If lon_deg is greater than or equal to bb.min_lon_deg:
            Set in_region to 1
        End If
        If lon_deg is less than or equal to bb.max_lon_deg:
            Set in_region to 1
        End If
        If in_region is equal to 0:
            Note: extend on the side requiring smaller move
            Let dist_to_min be bb.min_lon_deg minus lon_deg
            If dist_to_min is less than 0.0:
                Set dist_to_min to 0.0 minus dist_to_min
            End If
            Let dist_to_max be lon_deg minus bb.max_lon_deg
            If dist_to_max is less than 0.0:
                Set dist_to_max to 0.0 minus dist_to_max
            End If
            If dist_to_min is less than dist_to_max:
                Set new_min_lon to lon_deg
            Otherwise:
                Set new_max_lon to lon_deg
            End If
        End If
    End If
    Return proc bbox_create with new_min_lat, new_max_lat, new_min_lon, new_max_lon
End Process

Process called "bbox_union" takes a as BoundingBox, b as BoundingBox returns BoundingBox:
    @Reasoning:
        Smallest bbox enclosing both a and b. Treats both bboxes as
        non-wrapping for simplicity; antimeridian-aware union is
        delegated to the caller.
    @End Reasoning
    @Implementation:
        Min of mins, max of maxes.
    @End Implementation
    @Performance_Hints:
        Four compares.
    @End Performance_Hints
    @Security_Scope:
        Pure.
    @End Security_Scope
    Let lat_lo be a.min_lat_deg
    If b.min_lat_deg is less than lat_lo:
        Set lat_lo to b.min_lat_deg
    End If
    Let lat_hi be a.max_lat_deg
    If b.max_lat_deg is greater than lat_hi:
        Set lat_hi to b.max_lat_deg
    End If
    Let lon_lo be a.min_lon_deg
    If b.min_lon_deg is less than lon_lo:
        Set lon_lo to b.min_lon_deg
    End If
    Let lon_hi be a.max_lon_deg
    If b.max_lon_deg is greater than lon_hi:
        Set lon_hi to b.max_lon_deg
    End If
    Return proc bbox_create with lat_lo, lat_hi, lon_lo, lon_hi
End Process

Process called "bbox_intersection" takes a as BoundingBox, b as BoundingBox returns BoundingBox:
    @Reasoning:
        Geometric intersection of two non-wrapping bboxes. Returns
        a degenerate bbox (min > max in some axis) when disjoint;
        the caller can detect emptiness via bbox_is_empty.
    @End Reasoning
    @Implementation:
        Max of mins, min of maxes.
    @End Implementation
    @Performance_Hints:
        Four compares.
    @End Performance_Hints
    @Security_Scope:
        Pure.
    @End Security_Scope
    Let lat_lo be a.min_lat_deg
    If b.min_lat_deg is greater than lat_lo:
        Set lat_lo to b.min_lat_deg
    End If
    Let lat_hi be a.max_lat_deg
    If b.max_lat_deg is less than lat_hi:
        Set lat_hi to b.max_lat_deg
    End If
    Let lon_lo be a.min_lon_deg
    If b.min_lon_deg is greater than lon_lo:
        Set lon_lo to b.min_lon_deg
    End If
    Let lon_hi be a.max_lon_deg
    If b.max_lon_deg is less than lon_hi:
        Set lon_hi to b.max_lon_deg
    End If
    Return proc bbox_create with lat_lo, lat_hi, lon_lo, lon_hi
End Process

Process called "bbox_is_empty" takes bb as BoundingBox returns Integer:
    If bb.min_lat_deg is greater than bb.max_lat_deg:
        Return 1
    End If
    If bb.min_lon_deg is greater than bb.max_lon_deg:
        Note: This is also the antimeridian-wrap signal; the caller has
        Note: to disambiguate via bbox_crosses_antimeridian. We treat
        Note: empty only when latitude is degenerate.
        Return 0
    End If
    Return 0
End Process

Note: ============================================================================
Note: SECTION 3 - Containment predicates
Note: ============================================================================

Process called "bbox_contains_point" takes bb as BoundingBox, lat_deg as Float, lon_deg as Float returns Integer:
    @Reasoning:
        Point-in-bbox test. Latitude is inclusive on both ends; longitude
        is inclusive and handles antimeridian wrapping.
    @End Reasoning
    @Implementation:
        Latitude: lat in [min_lat, max_lat]. Longitude: if crossing,
        lon in [min_lon, 180] U [-180, max_lon]; else lon in [min_lon, max_lon].
    @End Implementation
    @Performance_Hints:
        Four compares (six if wrapping).
    @End Performance_Hints
    @Security_Scope:
        Pure.
    @End Security_Scope
    If lat_deg is less than bb.min_lat_deg:
        Return 0
    End If
    If lat_deg is greater than bb.max_lat_deg:
        Return 0
    End If
    Let crosses be 0
    If bb.min_lon_deg is greater than bb.max_lon_deg:
        Set crosses to 1
    End If
    If crosses is equal to 0:
        If lon_deg is less than bb.min_lon_deg:
            Return 0
        End If
        If lon_deg is greater than bb.max_lon_deg:
            Return 0
        End If
        Return 1
    End If
    If lon_deg is greater than or equal to bb.min_lon_deg:
        Return 1
    End If
    If lon_deg is less than or equal to bb.max_lon_deg:
        Return 1
    End If
    Return 0
End Process

Process called "bbox_contains_bbox" takes outer as BoundingBox, inner as BoundingBox returns Integer:
    @Reasoning:
        True iff every point in `inner` is contained by `outer`.
        Implemented for non-wrapping bboxes; wrapping cases return
        0 (caller should split first).
    @End Reasoning
    @Implementation:
        Compare each axis bound.
    @End Implementation
    @Performance_Hints:
        Four compares.
    @End Performance_Hints
    @Security_Scope:
        Pure.
    @End Security_Scope
    If outer.min_lon_deg is greater than outer.max_lon_deg:
        Return 0
    End If
    If inner.min_lon_deg is greater than inner.max_lon_deg:
        Return 0
    End If
    If inner.min_lat_deg is less than outer.min_lat_deg:
        Return 0
    End If
    If inner.max_lat_deg is greater than outer.max_lat_deg:
        Return 0
    End If
    If inner.min_lon_deg is less than outer.min_lon_deg:
        Return 0
    End If
    If inner.max_lon_deg is greater than outer.max_lon_deg:
        Return 0
    End If
    Return 1
End Process

Process called "bbox_intersects" takes a as BoundingBox, b as BoundingBox returns Integer:
    @Reasoning:
        True iff a and b share at least one common point on the sphere.
        Handles antimeridian-wrapping bboxes (min_lon > max_lon)
        per RFC 7946 GeoJSON convention: a wrapping bbox is the
        union of two non-wrapping sub-bboxes [min_lon, +180] and
        [-180, max_lon]. For each axis we test the four wrap-state
        combinations explicitly.
    @End Reasoning
    @Implementation:
        Latitude is monotonic (no wrap): single AABB disjoint test.
        Longitude has four cases:
          - Both non-wrapping: standard AABB disjoint test.
          - A wraps, B does not: A is [min_a, +180] U [-180, max_a].
            Intersection with B = [min_b, max_b] is non-empty iff
            B reaches into either arm: max_b >= min_a OR min_b <= max_a.
          - B wraps, A does not: symmetric.
          - Both wrap: both span the antimeridian so they always share
            the +/-180 line; return 1.
    @End Implementation
    @Performance_Hints:
        At most four longitude compares + two latitude compares.
    @End Performance_Hints
    @Security_Scope:
        Pure.
    @End Security_Scope
    Note: Latitude axis (no wrap)
    If a.min_lat_deg is greater than b.max_lat_deg:
        Return 0
    End If
    If a.max_lat_deg is less than b.min_lat_deg:
        Return 0
    End If
    Note: Longitude with antimeridian-wrap detection
    Let a_wraps be 0
    If a.min_lon_deg is greater than a.max_lon_deg:
        Set a_wraps to 1
    End If
    Let b_wraps be 0
    If b.min_lon_deg is greater than b.max_lon_deg:
        Set b_wraps to 1
    End If
    Note: Case 1: Both non-wrapping - standard AABB disjoint test on longitude.
    If a_wraps is equal to 0:
        If b_wraps is equal to 0:
            If a.min_lon_deg is greater than b.max_lon_deg:
                Return 0
            End If
            If a.max_lon_deg is less than b.min_lon_deg:
                Return 0
            End If
            Return 1
        End If
    End If
    Note: Case 2: A wraps, B does not. A covers [min_a, +180] U [-180, max_a].
    Note: Intersection non-empty iff B reaches either arm:
    Note:   B reaches eastern arm of A: b.max_lon_deg >= a.min_lon_deg
    Note:   B reaches western arm of A: b.min_lon_deg <= a.max_lon_deg
    If a_wraps is equal to 1:
        If b_wraps is equal to 0:
            If b.max_lon_deg is greater than or equal to a.min_lon_deg:
                Return 1
            End If
            If b.min_lon_deg is less than or equal to a.max_lon_deg:
                Return 1
            End If
            Return 0
        End If
    End If
    Note: Case 3: B wraps, A does not (symmetric to Case 2).
    If b_wraps is equal to 1:
        If a_wraps is equal to 0:
            If a.max_lon_deg is greater than or equal to b.min_lon_deg:
                Return 1
            End If
            If a.min_lon_deg is less than or equal to b.max_lon_deg:
                Return 1
            End If
            Return 0
        End If
    End If
    Note: Case 4: Both wrap - both span the antimeridian so they always overlap.
    Return 1
End Process

Note: ============================================================================
Note: SECTION 4 - Center, area, dimensions
Note: ============================================================================

Process called "bbox_min_lat" takes bb as BoundingBox returns Float:
    Return bb.min_lat_deg
End Process

Process called "bbox_max_lat" takes bb as BoundingBox returns Float:
    Return bb.max_lat_deg
End Process

Process called "bbox_min_lon" takes bb as BoundingBox returns Float:
    Return bb.min_lon_deg
End Process

Process called "bbox_max_lon" takes bb as BoundingBox returns Float:
    Return bb.max_lon_deg
End Process

Process called "bbox_center_lat" takes bb as BoundingBox returns Float:
    Return (bb.min_lat_deg plus bb.max_lat_deg) divided by 2.0
End Process

Process called "bbox_center_lon" takes bb as BoundingBox returns Float:
    @Reasoning:
        Center longitude. For wrapping bboxes the geometric center is
        on the opposite side of the antimeridian from the arithmetic
        mean, so we apply the standard correction: take the average,
        then wrap into [-180, +180] if necessary.
    @End Reasoning
    @Implementation:
        avg = (min + max) / 2. If the bbox wraps (min > max), add or
        subtract 360 from the smaller side first so the average lies
        on the wrapping side, then normalise the result back into
        [-180, +180].
    @End Implementation
    @Performance_Hints:
        ~ 8 cycles.
    @End Performance_Hints
    @Security_Scope:
        Pure.
    @End Security_Scope
    Let lo be bb.min_lon_deg
    Let hi be bb.max_lon_deg
    If lo is greater than hi:
        Set hi to hi plus 360.0
    End If
    Let avg be (lo plus hi) divided by 2.0
    If avg is greater than 180.0:
        Set avg to avg minus 360.0
    End If
    If avg is less than 0.0 minus 180.0:
        Set avg to avg plus 360.0
    End If
    Return avg
End Process

Process called "bbox_width_degrees" takes bb as BoundingBox returns Float:
    @Reasoning:
        Width of the bbox in longitude degrees. For wrapping bboxes
        this is (360 - max) + min, the angular distance traveled
        going east-to-west across the antimeridian.
    @End Reasoning
    @Implementation:
        Direct subtract; correct for wrapping.
    @End Implementation
    @Performance_Hints:
        Three compares.
    @End Performance_Hints
    @Security_Scope:
        Pure.
    @End Security_Scope
    If bb.min_lon_deg is greater than bb.max_lon_deg:
        Let part1 be 180.0 minus bb.min_lon_deg
        Let part2 be bb.max_lon_deg plus 180.0
        Return part1 plus part2
    End If
    Return bb.max_lon_deg minus bb.min_lon_deg
End Process

Process called "bbox_height_degrees" takes bb as BoundingBox returns Float:
    Return bb.max_lat_deg minus bb.min_lat_deg
End Process

Process called "bbox_area_approx_km2" takes bb as BoundingBox returns Float:
    @Reasoning:
        Approximate surface area of the bbox in square kilometres.
        For a small bbox at latitude phi the area is approximately
        (R^2 * cos(phi)) * dlat_rad * dlon_rad, with R the WGS84 mean
        radius in km (6371.0087). For visualization and indexing this
        is accurate to better than 1% for boxes spanning less than 10
        degrees of latitude.
    @End Reasoning
    @Implementation:
        Approximate cos(phi_center) via a Taylor series; multiply.
    @End Implementation
    @Performance_Hints:
        ~ 50 cycles.
    @End Performance_Hints
    @Security_Scope:
        Pure.
    @End Security_Scope
    Let R_km be 6371.0087
    Let phi_center_deg be proc bbox_center_lat with bb
    Let phi_center_rad be phi_center_deg multiplied by 0.017453292519943295
    Let cos_phi be proc bbox_cos_taylor with phi_center_rad
    Let dlat_rad be (proc bbox_height_degrees with bb) multiplied by 0.017453292519943295
    Let dlon_rad be (proc bbox_width_degrees with bb) multiplied by 0.017453292519943295
    Let area be R_km multiplied by R_km
    Set area to area multiplied by cos_phi
    Set area to area multiplied by dlat_rad
    Set area to area multiplied by dlon_rad
    If area is less than 0.0:
        Set area to 0.0 minus area
    End If
    Return area
End Process

Process called "bbox_cos_taylor" takes x as Float returns Float:
    Note: Local Taylor series for cos on [-pi/2, +pi/2] - identical to
    Note: ellipsoid_cos_taylor but inlined here to keep bounding_box
    Note: dependency-free of the ellipsoid module.
    Let x2 be x multiplied by x
    Let x4 be x2 multiplied by x2
    Let x6 be x4 multiplied by x2
    Let x8 be x6 multiplied by x2
    Let x10 be x8 multiplied by x2
    Let result be 1.0
    Set result to result minus (x2 divided by 2.0)
    Set result to result plus (x4 divided by 24.0)
    Set result to result minus (x6 divided by 720.0)
    Set result to result plus (x8 divided by 40320.0)
    Set result to result minus (x10 divided by 3628800.0)
    Return result
End Process

Note: ============================================================================
Note: SECTION 5 - Antimeridian handling
Note: ============================================================================

Process called "bbox_crosses_antimeridian" takes bb as BoundingBox returns Integer:
    If bb.min_lon_deg is greater than bb.max_lon_deg:
        Return 1
    End If
    Return 0
End Process

Process called "bbox_split_into_west_part" takes bb as BoundingBox returns BoundingBox:
    @Reasoning:
        For a bbox crossing the antimeridian, return the west part
        [min_lon, +180]. For a non-crossing bbox returns the same bbox.
    @End Reasoning
    @Implementation:
        Direct construction with longitude clamped at +180.
    @End Implementation
    @Performance_Hints:
        ~ 8 cycles.
    @End Performance_Hints
    @Security_Scope:
        Pure.
    @End Security_Scope
    If (proc bbox_crosses_antimeridian with bb) is equal to 0:
        Return bb
    End If
    Return proc bbox_create with bb.min_lat_deg, bb.max_lat_deg, bb.min_lon_deg, 180.0
End Process

Process called "bbox_split_into_east_part" takes bb as BoundingBox returns BoundingBox:
    @Reasoning:
        For a bbox crossing the antimeridian, return the east part
        [-180, max_lon]. For a non-crossing bbox returns the same bbox.
    @End Reasoning
    @Implementation:
        Direct construction with longitude clamped at -180.
    @End Implementation
    @Performance_Hints:
        ~ 8 cycles.
    @End Performance_Hints
    @Security_Scope:
        Pure.
    @End Security_Scope
    If (proc bbox_crosses_antimeridian with bb) is equal to 0:
        Return bb
    End If
    Return proc bbox_create with bb.min_lat_deg, bb.max_lat_deg, 0.0 minus 180.0, bb.max_lon_deg
End Process

Note: ============================================================================
Note: SECTION 6 - Predicates and equality
Note: ============================================================================

Process called "bbox_equals" takes a as BoundingBox, b as BoundingBox returns Integer:
    If a.min_lat_deg is not equal to b.min_lat_deg:
        Return 0
    End If
    If a.max_lat_deg is not equal to b.max_lat_deg:
        Return 0
    End If
    If a.min_lon_deg is not equal to b.min_lon_deg:
        Return 0
    End If
    If a.max_lon_deg is not equal to b.max_lon_deg:
        Return 0
    End If
    Return 1
End Process

Process called "bbox_equals_within_tolerance" takes a as BoundingBox, b as BoundingBox, tolerance_deg as Float returns Integer:
    Let d be a.min_lat_deg minus b.min_lat_deg
    If d is less than 0.0:
        Set d to 0.0 minus d
    End If
    If d is greater than tolerance_deg:
        Return 0
    End If
    Set d to a.max_lat_deg minus b.max_lat_deg
    If d is less than 0.0:
        Set d to 0.0 minus d
    End If
    If d is greater than tolerance_deg:
        Return 0
    End If
    Set d to a.min_lon_deg minus b.min_lon_deg
    If d is less than 0.0:
        Set d to 0.0 minus d
    End If
    If d is greater than tolerance_deg:
        Return 0
    End If
    Set d to a.max_lon_deg minus b.max_lon_deg
    If d is less than 0.0:
        Set d to 0.0 minus d
    End If
    If d is greater than tolerance_deg:
        Return 0
    End If
    Return 1
End Process

Process called "bbox_world" returns BoundingBox:
    @Reasoning:
        The full-world bbox covering all of Earth's surface.
    @End Reasoning
    @Implementation:
        (-90, +90) latitude, (-180, +180) longitude.
    @End Implementation
    @Performance_Hints:
        Four stores.
    @End Performance_Hints
    @Security_Scope:
        Pure.
    @End Security_Scope
    Return proc bbox_create with 0.0 minus 90.0, 90.0, 0.0 minus 180.0, 180.0
End Process
